
// Playwright + AI Agents — Quiz (20 questions, GIFT, English)

::Q1: What is Layer 4 in the AI testing landscape?::
{
=Autonomous agents that decide what to test and navigate UIs independently
~Self-healing locators that repair selectors
~AI-assisted authoring tools like Copilot
~Basic codegen tools like playwright codegen
}

::Q2: Which Playwright tool records user actions and generates code?::
{
=playwright codegen
~playwright run
~playwright inspector
~playwright tracegen
}

::Q3: What is a major limitation of raw codegen output?::
{
=It often produces fragile CSS/nth selectors requiring refactoring
~It cannot generate tests for navigation
~It only works with Firefox
~It produces code only in Java
}

::Q4: Which locator type is preferred over CSS nth-child selectors?::
{
=getByRole()
~locator('div > span:nth-child(3)')
~XPath selectors
~nth() positional selectors
}

::Q5: What does a smart locator strategy do?::
{
=Tries multiple fallback locator strategies in priority order
~Finds the shortest possible CSS selector
~Automatically rewrites HTML during testing
~Pauses execution to allow manual review
}

::Q6: What does the repairLocator() function attempt to do?::
{
=Ask an LLM to provide a replacement selector when the original breaks
~Retry the same selector up to 10 times
~Refresh the page automatically
~Switch the browser to headed mode
}

::Q7: What is the purpose of SelfHealingPage?::
{
=Detects broken selectors and generates repaired versions during test runtime
~Removes all AI-generated locators
~Optimizes Playwright performance
~Records test execution videos automatically
}

::Q8: Where is the healing report typically stored or attached?::
{
=Attached to testInfo as healing-report.json
~Saved to browser localStorage
~Stored in cookies by default
~Printed only to console with no file output
}

::Q9: What does an autonomous LLM-driven test agent rely on?::
{
=Screenshots + LLM reasoning to determine the next step
~Hardcoded selectors defined in config
~Fixed navigation sequences only
~Network request mocks for all interactions
}

::Q10: What is a key limitation of LLM agents?::
{
=They require oversight and may choose suboptimal actions
~They cannot take screenshots
~They only work with Chromium
~They disable Playwright’s auto-waiting
}

::Q11: What does the simple test agent loop require to operate?::
{
=A screenshot, the current page state, and an LLM decision
~A predefined JSON test plan
~Full application source code
~Only element IDs
}

::Q12: What does the Computer Use Agent allow Claude to do?::
{
=Control the browser at pixel-level using tool calls
~Write TypeScript directly without prompts
~Modify Playwright internal APIs
~Capture HAR files automatically
}

::Q13: In Computer Use mode, what is the purpose of tool_use blocks?::
{
=They specify browser actions like click, type, or move
~They log test metrics to CI
~They generate selectors automatically
~They record network traces
}

::Q14: What kind of prompt improves AI-generated tests?::
{
=Structured prompts with constraints and examples
~Random natural language instructions
~Prompts without context
~Prompts that forbid TypeScript
}

::Q15: What is one rule in Role + Constraint prompting?::
{
=Never use waitForTimeout()
~Always use nth selectors
~Avoid getByRole() locators
~Prefer XPath whenever possible
}

::Q16: What is the STAR prompt structure used for?::
{
=Designing clear testing prompts (Situation, Task, Action, Result)
~Generating random test data
~Creating browser contexts
~Mocking API calls
}

::Q17: What is migrateLocators.ts used for?::
{
=Modernizing spec files by replacing old locators
~Converting TypeScript tests to Python
~Generating screenshots for all tests
~Refactoring test names automatically
}

::Q18: What is the purpose of AI-generated test data?::
{
=Produce realistic, varied inputs for form testing
~Replace user prompts entirely
~Generate random CSS selectors
~Modify environment variables
}

::Q19: Why is few-shot prompting effective?::
{
=Examples help the LLM mimic desired code style
~It forces the LLM to shorten outputs
~It disables chain-of-thought reasoning
~It removes the need for context
}

::Q20: Which statement best describes Layer 3 (Self-healing)?::
{
=AI repairs broken selectors automatically at runtime or CI
~AI fully navigates the UI without instructions
~AI writes entire test suites alone
~AI only works inside your IDE
}

